{
  "category": "Uncategorized",
  "description": "Application-Layer Encryption for Sensitive User Data\n\nImplement transparent, application-layer encryption for all database columns that contain sensitive user-owned content, ensuring that Krisp developers and direct database access cannot read plaintext data while the application continues to function normally for authenticated users.\n\n---\n\nScope & Affected Tables\n\nIdentify and encrypt all columns containing sensitive user-authored or user-received content across the following surfaces (audit other tables during implementation for any overlooked PII):\n\n- `emails` table — subject, body, sender name, recipient fields, snippet\n- `meeting_transcripts` table — full transcript text, summary, key points\n- `meetings` table — title, description, participant names/emails\n- `action_items` table — title, description, notes\n- `kanban_cards` table — title, description, markdown body\n- `brain_thoughts` / Open Brain memory table — thought content, metadata, tags\n- `journal_entries` (if present) — all user-authored text fields\n- Any other table containing user-entered free text, names, or contact information\n\n---\n\nRequirements\n\nEncryption Strategy\n- Implement AES-256-GCM symmetric encryption at the application layer, before data is written to Neon PostgreSQL, so the database stores only ciphertext\n- Use a single master encryption key (MEK) stored in a secrets manager (environment variable as minimum viable approach; document upgrade path to AWS KMS, HashiCorp Vault, or Doppler)\n- Generate a unique initialization vector (IV) per field per write; store IV alongside ciphertext (e.g., as a prefixed, base64-encoded string in the same column or a companion column)\n- Do not encrypt columns used for filtering, sorting, or indexing (e.g., foreign keys, timestamps, status enums, boolean flags) — encrypt only free-text and PII payload columns\n\nKey Management\n- Define a `ENCRYPTION_KEY` environment variable (32-byte hex or base64) required at application startup; fail fast with a clear error if absent\n- Document key rotation procedure: introduce a `key_version` column or prefix on each encrypted field, write a migration script that re-encrypts all rows with the new key, and keep the old key available during the rotation window\n- Never log, expose via API response, or include in error traces the raw plaintext of encrypted fields\n\nEncryption Utility Module\n- Create a shared utility (e.g., `lib/encryption.ts`) that exports:\n  - `encrypt(plaintext: string): string` — returns a self-contained ciphertext string (IV + tag + ciphertext, base64-encoded)\n  - `decrypt(ciphertext: string): string` — reverses the above; returns plaintext\n  - `encryptNullable(value: string | null): string | null` — handles nullable columns safely\n  - `decryptNullable(value: string | null): string | null`\n- All encryption/decryption must occur in this single module; no ad-hoc crypto elsewhere in the codebase\n\nDrizzle ORM Integration\n- Apply encryption transparently at the data access layer rather than in individual route handlers or components\n- Introduce typed Drizzle custom column types or repository wrapper functions (`insertEncrypted`, `selectDecrypted`) so callers work with plaintext and encryption is invisible\n- Ensure Drizzle migrations do not alter column types for already-stored ciphertext (columns remain `text`); add a migration comment documenting that these columns store encrypted values\n\nVector Embeddings & Semantic Search\n- Embeddings (pgvector columns) are generated from plaintext before encryption; the embedding itself is not sensitive in isolation and does not need to be encrypted\n- Ensure the pipeline order is: plaintext → generate embedding → encrypt plaintext → store both; decryption must occur before any re-embedding on update\n\nSearch & Filtering Compatibility\n- Full-text Postgres search (`tsvector`, `ILIKE`) will no longer function on encrypted columns — document this explicitly and confirm that all full-text search paths have already migrated to vector embedding search (which operates on the embedding, not the stored text)\n- Any remaining keyword-filter queries against encrypted columns must be replaced with semantic search or moved to application-side filtering post-decryption\n\n---\n\nImplementation Steps\n\n1. Create `lib/encryption.ts` with AES-256-GCM encrypt/decrypt utilities and tests\n2. Audit all Drizzle schema files and produce a definitive list of columns to encrypt\n3. Write and run a one-time migration script to encrypt all existing plaintext rows in production (encrypt-in-place, column by column, with progress logging and a dry-run mode)\n4. Update all Drizzle insert/update call sites to encrypt before write\n5. Update all Drizzle select call sites to decrypt after read\n6. Update the Open Brain MCP server tools to decrypt thought content before returning to AI clients\n7. Update the Krisp webhook ingestion pipeline to encrypt transcript and key-point payloads on arrival\n8. Update the email ingestion pipeline (Graph API + Gmail) to encrypt subject, body, and sender fields on arrival\n9. Add startup validation that confirms `ENCRYPTION_KEY` is present and valid length\n10. Write integration tests that assert: (a) raw database reads return ciphertext, not plaintext; (b) application API responses return correct plaintext; (c) a missing or wrong key causes decryption to throw, not silently return garbage\n\n---\n\nEdge Cases & Considerations\n\n- Null and empty string handling — `null` stays `null`; empty string should encrypt to a non-empty ciphertext (do not special-case as null)\n- Partial migration failure — the in-place migration must be idempotent; detect already-encrypted rows by prefix marker (e.g., `enc:v1:`) and skip them\n- Session and cache invalidation — if any encrypted field values are cached in Redis, Next.js cache, or React Query, ensure cache keys or cache entries are invalidated after re-encryption during key rotation\n- API responses — decryption errors must return a 500 with a generic message, never expose the exception detail or partial plaintext to the client\n- Developer local environments — provide a deterministic test key for local development; document that production and staging must use separate, independently rotated keys\n- Backup and restore — encrypted backups of Neon remain encrypted at rest; document that a database restore without the corresponding `ENCRYPTION_KEY` value renders all user content unrecoverable; enforce key escrow policy",
  "title": "Implement application-layer encryption for sensitive user data",
